<ABS>  SUPPLEMENT </ABS>
<DATE1>   13 February 1994 </DATE1>
<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   WPROST Profile of Bogdan Pek </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94P20529B Poznan WPROST in Polish No 7, 13 Feb 94 p 6 </F>
<F P=103> 94P20529B </F>
<F P=104>  Poznan WPROST </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Polish </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article under the rubric "People": "Bogdan </F>
Pek"] 
  [Text] In comparing the sale of the Bank Slaski shares with 
the FOZZ (Fund for Servicing the Foreign Debt) affair, Bogdan 
Pek, a Sejm deputy representing the PSL (Polish Peasant Party, 
one of the coalition partners), set in motion a whole set of 
political and economic events: The discussion he started on the 
workings of the Polish stock exchange was one of the reasons for 
the fall in the share price, while Prime Minister Waldemar 
Pawlak dismissed Stefan Kawalec from his position as deputy 
minister of finance, thereby getting rid of his main opponent to 
the proposition of supporting the BGZ (Food Industry Bank) with 
the better part of the funds set aside in the budget for aiding 
the banks. 
  Bogdan Pek accused the bureaucrats in the Ministry of 
Finance 
of a rather large mistake in fixing the price of the Bank Slaski 
shares, adding that it was not they but rather the exchange and 
the economic condition of the enterprise that should have 
decided on the share price. In his opinion, the state budget was 
the loser in the privatization of Bank Slaski, while bank 
employees profited in availing themselves of "unjustified" 
preferences. In general, they cleared 5.8 trillion zlotys [Z]; 
management representatives profited by nearly Z15 billion. 
  Bogdan Pek was born in 1953 in Krakow. He completed the 
Zootechnical Department of the Academy of Agriculture. He is a 
professional politician: Active in the PSK [expansion unknown], 
he became a member of the Board of Directors and president of 
the Krakow branch of the party. In last year's parliamentary 
elections, he received 8,188 votes and, for the first time in 
his career, won a seat in parliament. In the Sejm, he serves as 
chairman of the Commission on Ownership Transformations [aka 
Privatization]. 
  He is married and has a 9-year-old daughter and an 
18-year-old son, who, he asserts, "would have priced the Bank 
Slaski shares better on his own calculator." His hobby is 
fishing. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

