<ABS>  SUPPLEMENT </ABS>
<DATE1>   6 March 1994 </DATE1>
<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   WPROST Profile of Hanna Gronkiewicz-Waltz </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94P20529D Poznan WPROST in Polish No 10, 6 Mar 94 p 6 </F>
<F P=103> 94P20529D </F>
<F P=104>  Poznan WPROST </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Polish </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article under the rubric "People": "Hanna </F>
Gronkiewicz Waltz"] 
  [Text] The report to members of parliament by Hanna 
Gronkiewicz-Waltz, president of the National Bank of Poland, on 
the condition of Polish banks states that only nine out of 15 
state banks has no problems. Of 1,664 cooperatives, 229 face the 
threat of liquidation or bankruptcy. Nor is the situation of 
private banks any better; only foreign banks may be said to have 
no problems. A commission has begun work, its aim being the 
creation of a new banking law and a study of ways to counteract 
the crisis situation. 
  Hanna Gronkiewicz-Waltz was born in 1952 in Warsaw. She is a 
graduate of the Department of Law and Administration of Warsaw 
University, a Ph.D. in legal theory, and a specialist in the 
area of banking law. She attended the Sorbonne for one year on a 
scholarship from the French Government. She was an adjunct 
professor at Warsaw University and at the Department of Canon 
Law at the Academy of Catholic Theology. In 1992, she was named 
director of Warsaw University's Institute of Law and National 
Economic Management. Earlier, beginning in 1989, she was the 
Sejm and Senate expert on public law affairs. From January to 
March 1992, she was the adviser to the director of the Analysis, 
Budget, and Finances Group of NIK [Supreme Board of Inspection]. 
  The first time Hanna Gronkiewicz-Waltz stood before the 
Commission on Economic Policy and Finances was in December 1991. 
At that time, her candidacy was dismissed by both the commission 
and the Sejm. In March 1992, supported by President Walesa, she 
was accepted and took on the position of president of the 
National Bank of Poland. The first major decision she 
implemented in that position was beginning the process of 
liquidation of the Bank of Commerce and Trade in Katowice. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

